<hl>
<seg id=1> A Chinese woman was violated in the riots in May; the Indonesian police questioned a reporter. </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> French News Agency, Jakarta The Committee of Protecting Journalists, an international organization of defending free journalism, was shocked at that the Indonesian police questioned a reporter because of his report that a Chinese woman was violated in the riots in May. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> According to the Committee of Protecting Journalists, New York Office, Gonawen, a reporter of " Jakarta- Jakarta", was questioned in the police headquarter on Thursday. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> The Committee said that in a report in July, Gonawen quoted a violated woman's talk. </seg>
<seg id=5> A report of the New York Times on 10 June also quoted the same victim's talk. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> The Committee said in a letter to Indonesian President Habibie that issuing a summons was "the first step for the police to charge a person". </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=7> The Committee was "worried a lot that such a law will cause a negative influence on freedom of speech". </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=8> What the Committee referred to was that under pressure from the Indonesian Islamic organization, the government was requested to arrest Gonawen according to the Criminal Law Act 156. </seg>
<seg id=9> According to the act, people are forbidden to slander any religious group. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=10> The International Independent Journalists' Association also protested against the police's summoning Gonawen. </seg>
<seg id=11> They said that this would " set a precedent, and weaken the greater freedom of journalism after the former president Suharto". </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=12> The Committee of Protecting Journalists requested Harbibie to "stop dealing with Gonawen", and asked all parties to settle the dispute in the civil court. </seg>
<seg id=13> They also called on all partied trying their best to remove the act of slander from the Indonesian Criminal Law." </seg>
</p>
